,Recommended,231740,11404054,"Posted: 25 July, 2014",all,OVERKILL_Almir,"Throwback RPG which does almost everything right that’s good with the genre; great XP system, classes, skills, character, achievement and item unlock systems - a great game."
,Recommended,231740,32995750,Posted: 29 June,all,Faudraline,"“The difference between the quest for the Holy Grail and someone saying ‘bring me a cup’ is the flavor text and the number of stops involved.” ― Bryan Fields,Life With a Fire-Breathing GirlfriendHailing from the indie developer, Behold Studios;Knights of Pen and Paperis an enjoyable throwback for any and all tabletop RPG gamer. It doesn't hold much brilliance in terms of either story or gameplay but makes you play the whole campaign with a persistent smile on your face anyhow. If you have spent your fair share of Saturday nights around a table, creating characters, passing each other various snacks and rolling the dice; you'll find the core concept of the game relatable and fun. If not, most of its content will be lost on you, so you could prefer avoiding this one. Being a chronic RPG gamer myself - both on tabletop and on PC - and still DMing for my various groups at age 30, this one hit the spot for me. It was all too familiar and successful in bringing tabletop humor to a PC game. So if you are an actual role-player - especially familiar with Dungeons and Dragons - go ahead. It's like someone decided to make a hotchpotch out of your regular Saturday night content, and even though you know it’s not the greatest dish in the world, you'd eat it 'cause it's familiar.I do bear a tradition of presenting an outline of the story in my reviews but here, there really isn't much to tell about - a bit of a disappointment, coming from a game about tabletop RPGs actually. Basically it's Saturday night, and a group of noob players huddle around their Dungeon Master and start a campaign. For the remainder of the game, your table will be the only constant between the game world and the real world. You'll be experiencing constant passages within these realities, as players constantly break the forth wall to comment or criticize the DM. Anything and everything within the game consist of RPG or Fantasy references and parodies, presented both during many out-game squabbles and relevant plot displays. As the storyline progresses DM will constantly bend the game world for it to fit into various RPG clichés. If you are familiar with the fantasy genre even remotely, you'll recognize at least a handful of given references. The baseline of the story is ""big baddies are cooking up vile plots, so we gotta beat them and get their loot"" pretty much. No depth there, but character squabbles and DM's commentaries on gameplay are funny and relatable. Thus, you keep playing the game even though it is a grind hell. So, this is what all this is about: spot on FRP parody.The game being a port from the mobile original, graphics are not demanding. It's a pixel run in a fantasy world with 8 bit music, coming from the same three tracks running in the background. It's fun and charming for a while, but kinda gets tiresome by the end. Still, there is some nostalgic spark in monster designs, that much I must agree with. With each new mob monster you'd come across, you'd catch a new reference. Would like to battle a gremlin? A doppelganger? A mimic? A dragon? Or even the Dark Knight? Do not look further.What about the gameplay? Well, this being a parody it certainly does its job on criticizing the power mechanic of many tabletop games. Everything is really, really basic. During battle, characters do bear 5 simple choices: attack, defend, use skill, use item or flee. That's it. The dice roll is not determinant during battle at all. It is presented only as a way for encounters to appear. There are a handful of classes you can pick, each having four skills which could be upgraded once at each level up. You attend quests - which are basically escort, slay or travel - to get exp, grind on monsters to do so, and pass for the next one. Yah, that's about all. It all boils down to gold, loot and exp, boys and girls. As the game progresses, mobs will get resistances and immunities, but combat mechanics never change. It is simplicity itself. Accompanied with the same 8 bit music over and over again, battles become really repetitive too. Once completed and the humor itself experienced, there really would not be any reason to revisit the game. So, there really isn't that much of a replay value, either.Well, I haven't shared any grand plusses about the game so far, did I? Mostly, I would say that it appeals to the common experience of tabletop gaming and parodies the DM/Player relationship based upon it. On doing so, the humor is successful, presenting you with many clichés, references and even some laughs. For someone who has never played a tabletop game? Nah, not so much. I would highly recommend for you to grab the game on sale if you are interested with the said humor, 'cause after going through the main game for 20 hours or so once, you won't be revisiting it. Enjoy, nonetheless!Please also check out Lady Storyteller's Curator pagehere- follow for regular updates on reviews for other games!"
,Recommended,231740,10457981,"Posted: 13 June, 2014",all,marcie,"There isn't much to this game; it's just a simple, humorous 8-bit turn base game. There is a lot of hilarious commentary and for the most part character development is nice. I know that the dialog is all pre-set, but it makes the characters pretty funny and sassy. One of my favorite aspects is the ridiculous dirty jokes made through-out the game.There's a ton (I mean A LOT) of characters and classes to choose from. There's a nice little upgrade setting that lets you have a few different moves and upgrade them.It's just like any other turn base game. It's fun, it's cheap and the developers are extremely nice and enjoy interacting with their fans; which is always great. I would definably get this game while on sale."
,Not Recommended,231740,7834907,"Posted: 29 November, 2013",all,Ryebread,"This has the appearance of a nostalgic D&D tabletop setting, but is more like a poorly-translated turn-based JRPG, where tactical positioning and well-timed skill choices are not the focus. Instead, players find themselves killing hordes upon hordes of monsters to make numbers go up so they can kill bigger hordes of scarier monsters. The story tries to be humorous about a D&D group finding the line between fantasy and reality blurred with numerous shoe-horned cameos, but the writing itself is unnatural to the point that it feels like a high-schooler's fan-fiction. In fact, if you're looking for a game the emulates the D&D experience, I recommend Cardhunter, a free-to-play tactical game with better writing and more involved gameplay.Even if you're in the market for a mindless grind-a-thon, don't buy this on the PC. Opt for the mobile version instead, since the game also constantly puts you through miniscule but unskippable animations that would be more bearable if you could look out the window while they play. Hell, I'd recommend other mobile games entirely, but some people like their skinner boxes and this is one of the skinneriest boxes I've ever seen.P.S.: This game *had* micro-transactions, but those have been removed. According to an anonymous source (see comment), the microtransaction was originally forced on by a publisher. A sad case of publisher overruling developer control. The game is still a terrible grind though."
