76561197980910801,Not Recommended,231740,8826157,"Posted: 23 January, 2014",all,Haute DIO,"It's not often that after only an hour of gameplay I don't feel the need to press on. The graphics are cute and the game sounds nice, but the gameplay and story are just not where they need to be. Yeah, the idea of playing a computer RPG about Pen & Paper RPGs is a cute idea, but the game is so damn meta that it actually feels like an amateur effort. Prepare to fight rats, goblins and evil wizards. Yawn. The character creation system looks very detailed at first, but then you realize that of the six initial classes, most only have 3 active skills and one passive skill for the ENTIRE game, and one or two have - gasp - FOUR skills. Here's every encounter in the game: rogue/mage use stuns, paladin use taunt, cleric heal, then attack, attack, attack, attack... Leveling up consists of upgrading one of your four skills, and weapons/armor upgrades require extreme grinding to level up your blacksmith to get a CHANCE at getting a straight upgrade. Oh and what's this? MICROTRANSACTIONS? In a game I already paid for? Even as a casual RPG, I would avoid getting this game at any price point. On a tablet? Maybe. On PC there are just way too many better indie titles at the same price point."
,Recommended,231740,8825151,"Posted: 23 January, 2014",all,Gungrave,This is quite possibly one of the more interesting games I've played in the past couple years and mind you I own 400+ games because it takes the classic Dungeons and Dragons board game and turns it into a sprite game while poking fun at the fact its all essentially imaginary and your characters make some funny comments now and then out of character lol.Overall the its a very well rounded game and I definately can't stop playing it.I'd say the only thing that is a negative point about the game is that to upgrade your gear you need to level up the blacksmith by collecting a literal f'ing s**t ton of an item called a Grindstone which to get them you buy them from the shop(waste of money) or mine them which takes f'ing forever. I found an exploit though that makes it easier to double the amount of grindstones you get. When you start the game to the east of the starting town is a cave where you can mine grindstones. When you click on one and the dice rolls up you need 6 or higher to get the grindstone. The key here is after clicking on the ore deposit just start pressing spacebar because once the dice stops rolling and you do or don't get the grindstone the act of pressing spacebar triggers the dice to reroll giving you another chance to get a grindstone. I went from getting around 10 grindstones every minute to around 20-25 grindstones in the same amount of time.
