76561198022848870,Not Recommended,231740,31240472,Posted: 19 April,all,gorbadoc23,"It's not a bad game. The experience opens strong, with a humor-rich premise and an uncomplicated-but-fun combat system. Unfortunately, the game leans too heavily on these, and it quickly gets repetitious. Just as important: Because the repetitious combat takes a long time, the game becomes boring.To see if the game would let me, I decided to take a level 30 quest when my party was level 8. I completed the quest, but it was the last satisfying experience of the game. Every fight was a little grindy: Sleep/stun everything, then focus fire on one enemy. Turn order is the same round after round, so there was no chance of me missing a lapsed sleep or stun. The stun-immune boss required a little more strategy, but it was still repetitious: paladin soaked; druid and witch kept paladin alive; wizard and rogue dealt damage (and occasionally stunned minions).When I got done with this quest, I thought, ""Ah, my party can beat level 30 content. Surely I'll burn through level 20 content like an acetylene torch through butter, so I can quickly advance this light, humorous storyline."" Not so. It turns out that I still have to spend a dozen rounds whittling down level 20 fights. The only difference is that, if I let a sleep or stun lapse, the consequences are lower, since the monsters don't hit as hard.Bottom line: I got some decent entertainment value out of Knights and Pen and Paper. I'm probably not going to finish it, though, and I can't say I would have missed much if I hadn't played it."
