,Not Recommended,231740,11790539,"Posted: 20 August, 2014",all,Sutalffa,"KPP+1 seems like an interesting concept, but it's really not. The theme is you actually roleplay players in a roleplaying world as characters.  You get the impression this is going to result in lots of humor and a diversity of environments where the players goof around in-character, but it doesn't happen.  Instead, you just end up picking a party of characters, optimize their performance with player personalities, buy add-ons for your gameroom that give character bonuses such as a better table or door, and meander through a roleplaying world which has little plot in itself nevermind the lack of out-of-character plot among the players.There isn't THAT much grinding if you do all the quests and use your items and gameroom bonuses appropriately to multiply the amount of experience and gold you get from battles, but you still have to complete slayer quests which are like how in MMOs you have to kill so many monsters for a reward.  The battle system is rather repetitive too.  Basically, you just get a taunting tank, heal it, and disable opponents while bombarding them with a magic dps and melee dps.  This goes on over and over with no change in tactics.  I say this despite how you can ""choose the difficulty"" by picking how many monsters you want to fight.  It's either you pick too little monsters to bother, pick just enough to repeat over and over, or pick too many to handle.  On the plus side, you can grab revive items in the shop in case your party dies out rather than paying the revive cost if you pick too many to handle, but it still doesn't make up for the repetition.This is compounded by the ridiculous investment needed to level up the blacksmith by buying ""grindstones"".  Each one costs 25 coins, yet the optimal levels of upgrading require around 100 grindstones.  Basically, that means you have to earn 6-7k coins, and when you're earning around 50-100 coins per fight until about 75% of the way through the game where you start earning 250-300 coins per fight, that means you're not going to experience using the blacksmith for a very long time.  You also need to buy enough luck amulets and great molten rings to make the optimal level cost effective, and you have to buy gameroom items to accelerate your income, so that's another 2-3k.  This ignores how you're spending coins on other things, so it really takes a long time just to unlock better equipment for your party.The campaign ultimately feels like a tutorial sampler of what the game has to offer.  Had the game included a custom campaign editor, this would be awesome since players could make their own material and share it in the community.  Heck, the campaign even feels like it'll unlock this towards the end in saying how the gameworld is much bigger than what you can see, but it never gets unlocked.  Also, the new classes you unlock are mostly pointless.  They're effective, but you have to level them up instead of being able to introduce them into the game right away, and that's a huge timesink.  Even if you play ""New Game+"" you still have to level them up.  This really stinks since it'd be nice to immediately jump into using a barbarian, knight, shaman, bard, and necromancer instead of a warrior, cleric, druid, mage, and rogue.  The game however just says, ""NO.  YOU DO HARD WAY OR NOT AT ALL!  GRRR!""On the other hand, if you start a plain old new game for the party, then you have to go through the hassle of upgrading the blacksmith all over again!  Don't forget the great molten rings or luck amulets too!  To be fair, you don't have to buy the income earning gameroom upgrades again, and you can technically grind out the income with your previous party in your other game since coins pool from all saved games, but still, you're talking about a good 8-9k in coins just to upgrade the blacksmith again. At that rate, you might as well just buy experience potions for 100 coins a pop to give everyone 6500 experience, plus you can buy the potion upgrades in the game room and use Ronaldo for the potion upgrade......but still, it's just more repetition.  This is supposed to be a roleplaying game instead of a railroad shooter.If the devs just spend a little more time on writing a plot, this game could have been awesome, but they didn't, so it flopped."
,Recommended,231740,25006361,"Posted: 18 August, 2016",all,_-=Groove=-_,"Congratulations to the Devs, excellent work!"
,Not Recommended,231740,7946639,"Posted: 6 December, 2013",all,プレアデス,"Having never played the classic tabletop D&D myself, I at first find the concept interesting however this turns up becoming a disappointment. The enjoyment value in this game is pretty inadequate.1) Clicking fiestaYou basically just need to click when you want to do almost anything. Just click the shop icon to buy item, just click the map button to travel, etc. You have control of the dungeon master. You get to choose what and how many enemies you want to fight with the limit of 7 (after unlocking it) same type of creature (combination is not possible). The combat system is pretty much lacking, and no brainer. There are only three damage type, physical, nature and magic. It doesn't matter if you hit enemies with ice or fire. The only option you have in organizing your party is pretty much who you want to include in the party (max. 5), no formation whatsoever. The ""threat level"" system is at best vague and unclear.2) Unclear storyline and boring questAfter playing this game for so long, I still have no idea what the story is about. Comments from the ""players"" range from boring to cheezy at best. The variations of sidequest are too little. Collect certain item from certain monster drop, kill certain amount of certain monster, escort someone (and 100% encounter at every place when you do this quest) and go to certain dungeon to fight with the developer. There ain't a puzzle for me to solve.3) Character creationCharacter creation is pretty much simple. Every ""player"" have his own bonus and you might want to make use of this bonus for the most fitting job. Each have 4 skills and set stats built. Everytime you level up, you have one skill point to spent. At first this seems okayish but as your level goes up, balance issue will be a slap on the face. Physical attack easily overpower magic skill. Leaving spellcasters as useless ragdoll.4) Bad economy and MicrotransactionThe main argument in the forum dwell on this ""innocent"" button on the top right corner. You can buy in game gold that you can earn by slaying monsters with real money. Why the heck it is there in a paid content anyway? Let me skip that annoyingly long argument. There are a few things that make people upset with the economy of the game. Firstly, the blacksmith. The only way to have better equipment is to go to the blacksmith (that can be found in some places) and have them upgraded for a fee. This process involve probabilistic element with success rate proportional with the level of the blacksmith. There are ways to reduce the cost and leveling the blacksmith without risking your gold but those are pretty much grinding. Secondly, you ""buy"" ""players"" with gold to start the game. There are ""players"" that are so expensive that it is impossible to start the game with without buying gold (on your first run). Thirdly, the gold is tied to your account, meaning that after your first run, you can start a second run with that amount that is left. This make second run pretty much broken as you probably have too much gold.5) The music is bad and annoying. It is getting on my nerves after a while."
