,Recommended,231740,28484994,"Posted: 20 December, 2016",all,爱阔少,"It was fun for like 2-3 hours, then becomes very repetitive.This game did very well at mimicking the tabletop RPG feeling. With the pixel art style and humors in story it brings you back to 80's when you sit with friends and roll some dice. Gameplay is quite casual and easy to pick up when you've got some time to kill.You can create a 5 members party, every member only have 4 skills, (some of them are passive skills) and there's no positioning. So there's really not much space for tactics, you'd probably be using the same way against all types of enemies. You can create a new member and exchange someone in your party to have some variety. But trying to level  up that guy is another long way to go. There are only limited amount of quests to do, after completing them all you can do is battle with some EXP/gold efficient monsters again and again.I stopped playing when find myself stuck at a boss and have to farm some money. To me, Knights of Pen and Paper = RPG in a nutshell. It shows me what I like and dislike in RPGs, without having all those fancy graphics, cut scenes, complex battle systems, large amounts of items. And I actually like this style, if you let me pick a game to play between Knights of Pen and Paper and Final Fantasy INSERT YOUR FAVORITE NUMBER, I'd probably still choose this one."
