,Recommended,231740,34026126,Posted: 4 August,all,agriba,"Knights of Pen and Paper is a simple, stream-lined rpg in the style of a table top rpg (ala, Dungeons and Dragons).This game is a barebones RPG, you have five characters with four abilities to level up and then you fight in turn based combat.  It's a tad slow, a tad simple, and highly repetitive.  Despite this, there are two good qualities: experimenting with all the classes and combinations is quite fun and the game takes some time before becoming grind-y.In addition to the base gameplay, there are a few other things going on.  A variety of quests which essentially all end up being just fighitng thigns over and over.  Different environments and enemies with a fun style.  A bunch of  flavor in the text.  And a ""crafting system"" that ends up just being collecting items to upgrade the blacksmith and pouring money into him to upgrade your characters in a very ineffecient method.With all that said, it may seems like this is a bad game, but in reality rating this game is hard.  It is cheap and the base gameplay is satisfying in that it is rewarding on a very simple way (much like incremental games) combined with almost brain-dead gameplay.It's definatly not for everyone, but Knights of Pen and Paper has its audiene.  Fans of Rpgs could get a few hours out of it before it beomes too grindy.  Those who enjoy incrimental games would probably get the most out of the game.  In the end its really just a question of what you expect for the price.  I'm giving it a thumbs up, but only for the right audience."
