76561197992856964,Recommended,231740,8840712,"Posted: 25 January, 2014",all,[FOR]mica,"This is a distressingly accurate tabletop simulator.It sort of feels like ""Dungeons of Dredmore Does Tabletop"" to me.  The sense of humor is mildly more down-to-earth, the battles are turn-based RPG style (with no tile-based / movement aspect), but the character progression is similar and the visual style reminds me of it in a good way.  The actual game mechanics are heavily simplified, and seem to be based as much off of japanese computer RPGs as they are off of any particular tabletop game.  The players for your party bicker and banter at eachother with one-liners now and again, I've found at least one quest that seems specifically designed to encourage lateral thinking (""why go to the area ten levels higher than you, when you can /buy/ the quest drop at a store?""), and there seems to be some kind of over-arching storyline that I haven't really gotten far with.DoD is on my computer as sort of an equivalent / replacement for solitaire -- Knights of Pen and Paper is happily getting added into the same category.[Edit]  On later reflection, it also reminds me of MMO's with the get quest / kill X things / get next quest / move to new area dynamic.  Unfortunately, they roam all over the world map and you can only hold one of them at a time -- meaning it's impossible to prioritize what order you want to do them in, particularly when many of them are multi-stage with each step in a different place.  There is very little strategy.  That said, it's still a good mindless game if you like the combat style."
