,Recommended,231740,13871158,"Posted: 6 January, 2015",all,WG4575,"I think I've played this game enough to give a basic review on the aspects of the game. Now, I'm going to go ahead and say that I like the style of this game, so I may be a bit biased. However, that does not matter as I will still be honest with this game.My reviews are typically divided into parts. Story, Gameplay, Music/Sounds, and Graphics. So let's get started!Graphics:I decided to start with graphics as they are the LEAST important when it comes to this review. This game is featured in 16 bit (I think) and looks quite good. In fact, you basically don't notice how old the graphics look after a while.Story:The story of this game is very simple. You are a adventurer. More specifically, you are a D&D player playing a character. You get to create your characters in this game, so you can mix and match until you find the ultimate party! You start with only two members at your table. However, you can pay gold to add three more party members. Each class has a different role. Paladin is the tank. Cleric is the healer. Mage is the support/dps and rogue is the 100% pure blood DPS. After you select your party members and their roles, you start by having your DM tell you that you are in a dark dungeon with no recollection of what happened to you previously. Now, I really don't want to spoil anymore, as fans of D&D (myself included) will have a very fun time with this game.Gameplay:This game features a turn-based system using ""initiative"", a real D&D mechanic. Initiative is rolled to see who gets to attack first. Say your character and an ogre were about to have a fight. Your character rolls a 15. The ogre rolls a 9. Therefore, you would get to go first, as you have the higher number. Not only is this game ROLLING in D&D references, it has it's own unique style. Locations are intresting, characters are hilarious and dialogue kept me laughing the entire time. For example, early in the game you have to kill some rats. The DM says a girl walks up to the party. One of your party members will ask, ""Is she hot?"" and your DM replies, ""Fine. Her charisma is 19."" See what I'm saying? So many tabletop references! I guess that's expected. You can upgrade your characters stats using ""table items"" like food or drinks. There are permanent table items, including a BK crown (which allows you to fight 7 monsters at once) and the Holy Grail (which allows you to have 5 members at your table). There are also ""room upgrades"". For example, on the left side of your room, you can have a suit of armor, which gives you +20 health on every character until you change it. On the right side, you can have a fridge, which makes your table items last longer. You can change your tables too. The gold table gives you more gold. The rock table gives you a larger crit chance. This game is full of customization!Music/Sounds:Music and sounds are, like the graphics, designed in a 16 bit fashion, delivering some tunes I've been humming since the day I got the game. The title screen is my personal favorite though!OVERALL RATING:This game is a fantastic game with a lot of comedy. Over all I'd give Knights of Pen and Paper +1 Edition a 10/10 for it's effort to contribute to the D&D society and give you some good laughs along the way!Conclusion:I hope you enjoyed my review of Knights of Pen and Paper +1 Edition! The DLC for the game, Haunted Fall, is out now! I will be reviewing it once I get the chance to play the DLC! Cya next time folks!"
