,Recommended,231740,14655832,"Posted: 25 February, 2015",all,ObiJuan,"So, understand right off the bat that this is a mobile phone port -- nothing more, nothing less.  As such, it's overpriced (twice as much as the mobile app), but I would still recommend it.  I've played it on the phone and on the laptop, so I've played much more than the 13 hours it shows.Imagine a D&D mod for a Final Fantasy game, and that's largely how Knights of Pen and Paper plays -- D&D feel, FF-type mechanics.It has a great variety of traditional D&D classes (though simplified and somewhat reimagined for the FF-type mechanics), and each class really does play differently from the others.  Sure, you have your traditional D&D roles that each one fits, but they're not just strikers, glass cannons, rogues, etc with different skins.  For example, even though they are all traditionally tanks/strikers, a paladin is not a warrior is not a barbarian in this game.You also have classes that excel verseus single targers, excel versus groups, and some that can do both fairly well.  The true variety between classes is probably the game's greatest selling point, in my opinion.  No two parties will feel the same, giving the game great replay value.You also RP as the DM, as well as the players.  This lets you do things like decide exactly how hard most battles will be (with more xp for more/harder enemies).  It's a nice little touch.Overall, buy it on sale without even thinking about it! Seriously! Pounce on any sale at all!For full price, you probably need to have some D&D nostalgia to make it worth the $10."
