76561198212093451,Recommended,231740,31185140,Posted: 16 April,all,Pneumarian,"I've only tabletopped a couple times, & the oldest D&D edition I've used was 3.5, so I'm hardly the target audience anyway. I found the combat system to be more Final Fantasy, (which I've played even less,) than D&D.There's no apparent plot, which was even less than I expected, but not actually less than advertised. Of course, I like being at least double my opponent's level, so I wouldn't be following the storyline at the proper pace anyway. I only just found where the blacksmith is, perhaps now that I can improve my weapons & armour, I'll dawdle less. Just as soon as I get my gear leveled up sufficiently.Some reviewers have complained about the boring dialog. In my experience the dialog rarely displays for sufficient time to properly notice that it's even there, let alone read it. Maybe that's why I haven't caught the plot.Pretty good for filling a few unallocated minutes, or hours of meaningless hack-n-slash. Not recommended for when you want a strong story."
,Recommended,231740,19601586,"Posted: 10 December, 2015",all,Syrsly,"Fun game, Pen And Paper is!Knights Of Pen And Paper +1is one of those games I wish I bought for my phone rather than my PC, because it has simplistic visuals and a touch-friendly interface.  That said, after playing it for so long on here, I really enjoyed it enough to consider getting the phone version as well.  It has a lot of replay value due to its insanelygrindyRPG features and its humor.The game's content is often based on external references, including Half-Life and Steam, but the base concept of the game's plot and visuals is that you are a party of Dungeons And Dragons - or a similar table top RPG - players trying to enjoy a night of role-playing.The plot starts to unravel into a quest to save both the pen and paper universe and the real world when a mage starts to cross into their dimension from the game.The overall plot is very humorous and filled with nice cameo appearances by both the game development team and a variety of real world influences.  My personal favorite cameo wasNabe Gewell (Gabe Newell) on Steam Island.Overall, the gameplay is like something out of RPG Maker but ultimately more streamlined and customized than that.  The battles are turn-based and involve up to five player characters and up to seven enemy characters.  The battle system also involves status effects, including stun, sleep, poison, bleed, weaken, strengthen, and other boosts.  Each character/class acts differently in battle, allowing for a lot of strategizing during tough battles.  Battles are fun but also sometimes tedious.  There is a major grind to this game that some people may not appreciate, but I enjoy having long-term content, even if it's just a grind of stats and a bunch of high-powered enemies."
,Recommended,231740,31686588,Posted: 11 May,all,Proskub,"I really enjoyed the first few hours of this game but now that I am approaching the end game, I need to spend an unenjoyable amount of time grinding. I think its a common thing as well because in the games ""Deluxier edition"" description there is a line that says ""farm experience efficiently"" which makes me think that its an implemented game feature. I don't like it, others may. Now, I think its a good game to buy during a sale, because I dont think it would be worth the 10$ price tag. I would be happy to pay 2-5$ for this game.I am recommending this game because its fun enough to make a little party, enjoy the meta-banter, and experience all the work the devs put into the game such as the locations and monsters. I enjoyed it more than I didnt enjoy the grind."
